EXPLANATION – Matter in bolded italics is new; matter between brackets [omitted material] is material to be omitted.
AN ACT relating to law enforcement; requiring that a peace officer
compelled to appear as a witness in certain investigations
receive written notice within a certain time of the
obligation to appear for an interview; requiring that a
peace officer compelled to appear as the subject of an
investigation receive written notice that states certain
matters with specificity; and providing other matters
properly relating thereto.
Legislative Counsel’s Digest:
1 Existing law authorizes a law enforcement agency to conduct an investigation
2 of a peace officer in response to a complaint or allegation that the peace officer
3 engaged in activities which may result in punitive action. (NRS 289.057) If a law
4 enforcement agency initiates an investigation of a peace officer, existing law
5 requires that written notice be provided to the peace officer not later than 48 hours
6 before any interrogation or hearing and that the written notice include a summary of
7 the peace officer’s alleged misconduct. (NRS 289.060) Section 1 of this bill
8 requires that the written notice include a summary that sets forth with specificity
9 the alleged acts or omissions constituting the misconduct and the date, time and
10 location of the alleged misconduct. If the date, time or location is unknown, the
11 summary must specify that the date, time or location is unknown. Existing law also
12 requires that an investigating agency provide written notice before compelling a
13 peace officer to appear and be interviewed as a witness in connection with an
14 investigation. (NRS 289.060) Section 1 prohibits a law enforcement agency from
15 interviewing a peace officer as a witness on less than 48 hours’ written notice.
16 Section 1 specifies that such notice must be provided not later than 48 hours before
17 the peace officer must appear and be interviewed.
