1 for the interview or interrogation to be deemed a part of the peace
2 officer’s regular working hours. Any such time must be calculated
3 based on the peace officer’s regular wages for his or her regularly
4 scheduled working hours. If the peace officer is not interviewed or
5 interrogated during his or her regular working hours or if his or her
6 work schedule is not revised pursuant to this paragraph and the law
7 enforcement agency notifies the peace officer to appear at a time
8 when he or she is off duty, the peace officer must be compensated
9 for appearing at the interview or interrogation based on the wages
10 and any other benefits the peace officer is entitled to receive for
11 appearing at the time set forth in the notice.
12 (b) Immediately before any interrogation or hearing begins,
13 inform the peace officer who is the subject of the investigation
14 orally on the record that:
15 (1) The peace officer is required to provide a statement and
16 answer questions related to the peace officer’s alleged misconduct;
17 and
18 (2) If the peace officer fails to provide such a statement or to
19 answer any such questions, the agency may charge the peace officer
20 with insubordination.
21 (c) Limit the scope of the questions during the interrogation or
22 hearing to the alleged misconduct of the peace officer who is the
23 subject of the investigation. If any evidence is discovered during the
24 course of an investigation or hearing which establishes or may
25 establish any other possible misconduct engaged in by the peace
26 officer, the law enforcement agency shall notify the peace officer of
27 that fact and shall not conduct any further interrogation of the peace
28 officer concerning the possible misconduct until a subsequent notice
29 of that evidence and possible misconduct is provided to the peace
30 officer pursuant to this chapter.
31 (d) Allow the peace officer who is the subject of the
32 investigation or who is a witness in the investigation to explain an
33 answer or refute a negative implication which results from
34 questioning during an interview, interrogation or hearing.
35 4. If a peace officer provides a statement or answers a question
36 relating to the alleged misconduct of a peace officer who is the
37 subject of an investigation pursuant to NRS 289.057 after the peace
38 officer is informed that failing to provide the statement or answer
39 may result in punitive action against him or her, the statement or
40 answer must not be used against the peace officer who provided the
41 statement or answer in any subsequent criminal proceeding.
